Purpose
The Mirror Arrays provide concentrated light for high‑temperature processes on the RAMA Hub.
Their primary role is to support the factories by delivering focused heat to the ovens, reducing electrical load and increasing throughput.

They are simple, passive, and fully serviceable.

Array Architecture
Flat or slightly curved reflective panels

Mounted on lightweight adjustable booms

Positioned around the hub for optimal sunlight capture

Each mirror is identical for manufacturing simplicity

The arrays are modular — add more mirrors, get more heat.

Function
The Mirror Arrays:

Concentrate sunlight onto factory ovens

Reduce electrical heating requirements

Allow factories to run hotter with less power

Provide a stable, predictable thermal input

Operate with no moving parts except simple angle adjustments

This keeps the factories efficient without adding complexity.

Mounting & Orientation
Mirrors attach to standardized hardpoints on the Support Layer

Booms extend outward to avoid shading solar arrays

Angle can be adjusted during installation or maintenance

No active tracking required — simple manual set‑and‑forget geometry

Maintenance & Replacement
MOEs can:

Swap damaged mirrors

Replace entire mirror modules

Add new mirrors as factory demand increases

All mounts use standardized brackets and cable anchors

Design Philosophy
Passive: No motors, no actuators, no tracking systems

Modular: Add or remove mirrors as needed

Serviceable: Every component is MOE‑replaceable

Robust: Built to survive decades of orbital sunlight

Efficient: Provides free heat without consuming electrical power

Why This Matters
The Mirror Arrays:

Boost factory throughput

Reduce electrical load on the solar arrays

Enable higher‑temperature processing

Scale easily as RAMA expands

Provide a simple, reliable thermal input

Mirrors are the quiet workhorses that make orbital manufacturing more efficient.
